data.name: marketing
data.description:
The data consists of 1926 households with 8 variables from questionnaires and & business records. It's pretty outdated data from the early 1990s. The variable names in mktg.col explain most:
lincons log of minutes of incoming calls loutcons log of minutes of outgoing calls ltotrev log of total revenue bustools need business tools, Y/N (fax, PC,...) reach need tools to reach family, friends, Y/N (beeper, cell phone,...) children have children, Y/N agegroup age group, 5 grps educ education level, 7 grps
Some might object to doing k-means and princ comps in the presence of binary variables, but that's business practice. The proof is in the success of the analysis. In this case, 4-means clustering yields a neat segmentation of the data into sectors of the plane spanned by the first two principal components. [This is not surprising in view of results by Tad Tarpey.]
An important point is that although we use a "clustering method" (k-means), we're not finding isolated clusters but merely a "segmentation" into four homogeneous subsets. In marketing there are almost never natural clusters. The data usually form oval "pies" in data space, and the task is to neatly cut the pie into compact slices, which k-means does quite nicely.
